sports events for the little league or something,

00:01:49.719 --> 00:01:54.400
publish that out to a server and we provided a way
to do that through .Mac you didn't have to set

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:58.230
up your own server and you can share calendars that way.

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:05.250
But once again, that was just a read-only
and only one person can edit that calendar.

00:02:05.250 --> 00:02:10.539
iPhone version 1 followed along and again, it
included a calendar application that was geared

00:02:10.539 --> 00:02:14.549
at personal calendaring much like iCal version 1 was.

00:02:14.550 --> 00:02:22.540
Then with iCal 3, we actually introduced CalDAV, and CalDAV
gave iCal the ability to actually store events on a server

00:02:22.539 --> 00:02:28.889
in a more interesting way than it could with just WebDAV,
and that allowed people to actually schedule meetings

00:02:28.889 --> 00:02:31.919
with each other, where I can invite you to
a meeting and you can accept or decline.

00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:38.709
I could see when you are available for that meeting
and it obviated the need for iSync as a solution

00:02:38.710 --> 00:02:43.830
because now I can get all-- all my computers can get
to the CalDAV server directly and get that data down,

00:02:43.830 --> 00:02:47.630
and it added additional functionality on top of that.

00:02:47.629 --> 00:02:53.349
iPhone 2 added support for that same functionality
when you were talking to a Microsoft Exchange Server

00:02:53.349 --> 00:02:59.269
which is a highly demanded feature for people in
the business center for I's [phonetic] market.

00:02:59.270 --> 00:03:07.530
And then with iCal 4, they added also support for
exchange and with iPhone 3, we had now have the ability

00:03:07.530 --> 00:03:13.129
to speak to iCal Server via CalDAV, so thanks.

00:03:13.129 --> 00:03:18.939
CalDAV is actually kind of the glue that holds
all of our calendaring solutions together.

00:03:18.939 --> 00:03:25.250
All of the Apple products now speak one common
protocol, that's an open standard that not only Apple

00:03:25.250 --> 00:03:30.719
but actually several other players in the
calendaring marketplace participate in.

00:03:30.719 --> 00:03:38.180
So, let's talk just briefly, give you an overview what
CalDAV provides in terms of protocol and standards.

00:03:38.180 --> 00:03:44.659
First up, we leverage iCalendar which is a text data
format that basically specifies when a meeting is,

00:03:44.659 --> 00:03:50.810
what its title is, who the attendees are, when it
ends, does it recur, does it happen on every full moon

00:03:50.810 --> 00:03:54.129
of the third month of every year, that sort of thing.

00:03:54.129 --> 00:03:58.030
It's actually a pretty rich way
to describe meeting information.

00:03:58.030 --> 00:04:04.879
iTIP is the iCalendar transport
interchange protocol, I believe,

00:04:04.879 --> 00:04:08.460
and that allows you to basically schedule with other people.

00:04:08.460 --> 00:04:13.090
Lets you say send the messages as when
are you available for a meeting or, "Hey,

00:04:13.090 --> 00:04:15.950
I'd like you to come to this meeting, can you come?"

00:04:15.949 --> 00:04:19.899
Now these two standards have been
around for a good long time,

00:04:19.899 --> 00:04:25.939
and they're supported by pretty much every
calendaring software system that's out there today,

00:04:25.939 --> 00:04:30.829
that includes Microsoft Outlook, that includes
iCal going all the way back to version 1

00:04:30.829 --> 00:04:35.759
and pretty much everything you use,
Mozilla calendar and that sort of thing.

00:04:35.759 --> 00:04:41.189
Now we wanted to take these things and be able to
store them on a server, and the protocol that seems

00:04:41.189 --> 00:04:44.519
to be very well regarded for doing
that sort of thing is HTTP,

00:04:44.519 --> 00:04:49.399
but in order to facilitate that,
you need WebDAV which leverages XML.

00:04:49.399 --> 00:04:55.669
And with extensions for access control, you can
actually manage who is allowed to do what on a server.

00:04:55.670 --> 00:05:00.850
And then the CalDAV access protocol
uses iCalendar and WebDAV in order

00:05:00.850 --> 00:05:03.700
to give you the ability to store that data on a server.

00:05:03.699 --> 00:05:10.469
CalDAV schedule gives you the ability to-- with
iTIP actually do delivery of scheduling messages.

00:05:10.470 --> 00:05:17.700
Now, CalDAV access was made into an RFC
recently, so that's already an internet standard.

00:05:17.699 --> 00:05:22.349
CalDAV schedule is starting to wrap up and is
actually very close to getting to that level,

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:25.480
but iCal Server's been supporting these all along.

00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:31.939
So, there are a lot of players as I mentioned that are
involved in this space, of course that includes Apple,

00:05:31.939 --> 00:05:40.980
but also IBM which is a huge player in calendaring-- Scalix,
Mozilla, Yahoo and Google, Kerio, and so on and so forth.

00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:44.939
