And again, one of the key things we want to
do with all of our client interactions is just

00:17:59.069 --> 00:18:01.559
to make this as easy as possible for the user.

00:18:01.559 --> 00:18:07.099
So now the process of actually configuring
an account in iCal is pretty straightforward.

00:18:07.099 --> 00:18:11.879
Basically, you just need to provide your email
address and your password and iCal will actually go

00:18:11.880 --> 00:18:14.510
and use a suitable order discovery mechanism

00:18:14.509 --> 00:18:19.849
to determine what is the Calendar Server that's
appropriate for that particular email address.

00:18:19.849 --> 00:18:23.769
Now you can if you want, you know, you can
choose the Automatic option and iCal will try all

00:18:23.769 --> 00:18:29.619
of the different possibilities suitable or
you can explicitly say CalDAV or Exchange

00:18:29.619 --> 00:18:33.159
and also configure at Google or Yahoo directly.

00:18:33.160 --> 00:18:36.630
We're going to stick with automatic
for the time being and I'm just going

00:18:36.630 --> 00:18:43.980
to enter my information here, my
email address and my password.

00:18:43.980 --> 00:18:46.200
I'm going to click Create.

00:18:46.200 --> 00:18:47.769
So iCal is going out.

00:18:47.769 --> 00:18:48.910
It's searching the DNS.

00:18:48.910 --> 00:18:54.730
It's doing DNS SRV record lookouts to find the
local CalDAV Server for my particular domain

00:18:54.730 --> 00:18:56.960
that returns the host name and port information.

00:18:56.960 --> 00:19:04.390
So, you know, the service settings information that you see
here, all of this information was automatically determined

00:19:04.390 --> 00:19:07.860
by iCal by doing these DNS queries
or the discovery lookouts.

00:19:07.859 --> 00:19:11.199
So, a very simple process for the end
user to set up and configure accounts.

00:19:11.200 --> 00:19:19.400
So let's actually look at some of
the data that we have on the server.

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:27.420
With both-- with the Exchange support, you know,
we have here an event that was created on Exchange

00:19:27.420 --> 00:19:34.210
and this was an event that was the Suits
CEO John was inviting me to a meeting

00:19:34.210 --> 00:19:37.190
and I've got the option of accepting or declining as usual.

00:19:37.190 --> 00:19:42.980
I'm not actually going to do that at this point because
we're going to see how that works on the iPhone in a minute.

00:19:42.980 --> 00:19:46.150
Again, creating-- let's create--
actually create an event on Exchange.

00:19:46.150 --> 00:19:48.080
So I got my Exchange calendar set up here.

00:19:48.079 --> 00:19:51.220
I'm going to go in here.

00:19:51.220 --> 00:19:55.670
Create another meeting and I want to add some invitees.

00:19:55.670 --> 00:20:00.560
So iCal is actually going to use the contact
information from the system that I have here.

00:20:00.559 --> 00:20:06.119
Remember, Address Book also supports Exchange,
Address Book also supports Address Book Server

00:20:06.119 --> 00:20:09.049
and you can have local address information
in Address Book and iCal can pull

00:20:09.049 --> 00:20:11.649
that information from Address Book as well.

00:20:11.650 --> 00:20:17.540
>> So I already have John configured in my Address
Book, so I can just type a part of his name in there

00:20:17.539 --> 00:20:22.500
and we have an invite ready to send to John, but let's
actually just have a quick look at his availability.

00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:27.819
So in iCal, again, I did a free/busy lookup, but
this time it's the Exchange Server that we're dealing

00:20:27.819 --> 00:20:34.470
with so iCal went to Exchange and actually queried
for John's free/busy information for Thursday.

00:20:34.470 --> 00:20:39.259
And we can see that he was actually free at the time
that we've picked, so this looks-- this looks OK.

00:20:39.259 --> 00:20:43.140
I'm going to click Done here and
I'm going to send that off to John.

00:20:43.140 --> 00:20:47.970
So we just did a very simple scheduling
operation with Exchange.

00:20:47.970 --> 00:20:52.110
Let's do the same thing on iCal Server.

00:20:52.109 --> 00:21:02.019
So I'm going to create-- I need to select iCal Server
first over here, and I'm going to create a green meeting.

00:21:02.019 --> 00:21:11.119
So we want to schedule, just to go through the same
process, meeting history and again, I'm going to--

00:21:11.119 --> 00:21:14.419
I want to invite some people that are on my iCal Server.

00:21:14.420 --> 00:21:21.269
Now in Leopard, iCal actually required the client
machine to be bound to OpenDirectory in order

00:21:21.269 --> 00:21:24.599
for the Attendee Order Completion Facility to work.

00:21:24.599 --> 00:21:30.419
Basically, the directory was providing the user information
to the calendar server, iCal could buy into the directory

00:21:30.420 --> 00:21:34.789
and get that same information and use that
to order complete the addresses of attendees

00:21:34.789 --> 00:21:37.609
that are known to be supported on that Calendar Server.

00:21:37.609 --> 00:21:42.859
Well, one of the things that we changed in Snow Leopard is
to remove the need for the client machines to actually buy

00:21:42.859 --> 00:21:46.369
in to OpenDirectory in order to
get the attendee information.

00:21:46.369 --> 00:21:50.629
So this machine is not actually bound to the
directory, but the server is bound to this.

00:21:50.630 --> 00:21:53.340
Server still gets its user information from the directory

00:21:53.339 --> 00:21:56.250
but the client machines don't need
to buy into the directory anymore.

00:21:56.250 --> 00:22:03.000
Instead, what we've done is used facilities in the
WebDAV Protocol to allow the clients to actually search

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.400
through WebDAV to find information
about users on the system.

00:22:06.400 --> 00:22:12.210
So in WebDAV, users are each represented by a principal
resource on the server, and there's a query report

00:22:12.210 --> 00:22:17.710
that the client can do to actually say, "Tell me about
all the users with a particular name or of these letters"

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:20.160
that we can do in order to complete operations there.

00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:26.650
So, if I start typing, iCal is going out to the Calendar
Server, making a query of the Calendar Server in order

00:22:26.650 --> 00:22:30.769
to complete those letters that I type
and it comes back with a few names.

00:22:30.769 --> 00:22:38.319
So again, I can type in several names here, and in real time
we're going to query the server and get that information.

00:22:38.319 --> 00:22:43.960
And just like with-- with the Exchange event we just
created, I can pull up the availability information

00:22:43.960 --> 00:22:48.460
and again, get in real time, free/busy
information from iCal Server.

00:22:48.460 --> 00:22:50.870
So again, the same process that we can do in Exchange,

00:22:50.869 --> 00:22:54.500
we can do exactly the same thing with
our iCal Server, it's no different.

00:22:54.500 --> 00:22:56.829
The users don't have to do a context switch.

00:22:56.829 --> 00:22:59.149
In their mind just think "OK, I'm
doing something on Exchange.

00:22:59.150 --> 00:23:02.550
I have to do it differently over here or do
something in iCal Server different here."

00:23:02.549 --> 00:23:03.329
None of that.

00:23:03.329 --> 00:23:04.220
Everything is the same.

00:23:04.220 --> 00:23:05.890
The interactions are the same.

00:23:05.890 --> 00:23:10.720
So in this case, I'm going to click Done,
we're going to send that meeting off

00:23:10.720 --> 00:23:17.420
and the attendees can reply to that in a-- in a usual way.

00:23:17.420 --> 00:23:23.400
Now, another thing that's different about Snow Leopard
Server is that we now have the ability to schedule

00:23:23.400 --> 00:23:26.970
with users who are not actually hosted by the server itself.

00:23:26.970 --> 00:23:35.089
So in that particular example, I actually typed in the names
of attendees who are known to be on-- on my Calendar Server.

00:23:35.089 --> 00:23:40.990
But let's say I want to schedule with someone who's-- who
only has a Gmail account, and a Google Calendar account.

00:23:40.990 --> 00:23:42.549
Well, we can now do that in Snow Leopard.

00:23:42.549 --> 00:23:48.700
So I'm actually going to add the name
of my friend Elisa who I have configured

00:23:48.700 --> 00:23:51.420
in my Address Book with her Gmail account information.

00:23:51.420 --> 00:23:56.160
So I'm going to add her to that event,
and I'm going to click Update to update

00:23:56.160 --> 00:23:59.410
that event and put that back up on the server.

00:23:59.410 --> 00:24:02.910
Now, what's happening in the background is,
iCal is storing that event on the server.

00:24:02.910 --> 00:24:05.850
The server is passing out all the attendee information.

00:24:05.849 --> 00:24:09.219
It's spotting that Elisa is not
actually a user hosted by that server.

00:24:09.220 --> 00:24:11.779
But we specified an email address for her.

00:24:11.779 --> 00:24:17.029
So the server can be clever and create and iMIP message
which is basically an iCalendar attachment imbedded

00:24:17.029 --> 00:24:22.660
in email, it can create that message and actually
send it to Elisa's email account at Gmail.

00:24:22.660 --> 00:24:27.920
So let's actually see what Elisa gets to see on her end.

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:36.250
So I'm going out live to Google right now, and yup,
we see that there's a new event in Elisa's inbox here.

00:24:36.250 --> 00:24:38.960
Let me double-click on that to bring that up.

00:24:38.960 --> 00:24:42.470
OK, so we've got information for the event
that we just created and sent to Elisa.

00:24:42.470 --> 00:24:47.110
So we got a nice big icon there letting her know
exactly when that event is, we got the details, who's--

00:24:47.109 --> 00:24:50.959
who's the organizer, with information
about the other attendees.

00:24:50.960 --> 00:24:53.039
Now, Elisa has a couple of choices here.

00:24:53.039 --> 00:24:56.769
She has the option of replying
directly from this email message.

00:24:56.769 --> 00:25:03.180
She can say "Yes,"Maybe," or "No" right here in the
email, or she can actually go to her Google Calendar.

00:25:03.180 --> 00:25:10.000
Now as it turns out, Google's integrated system allows
it to take that iCalendar, attach it from email,

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:11.619
and automatically put it on her calendar.

00:25:11.619 --> 00:25:14.139
So it's already on her calendar when she goes to look at it.

00:25:14.140 --> 00:25:18.450
And again, if you pull up the details for this event,
she can see all the relevant information about attendees

00:25:18.450 --> 00:25:23.819
et cetera, and she can actually
reply directly from her calendar.

00:25:23.819 --> 00:25:30.409
So, what Google is now doing is again creating an
iMIP message which is a reply to the one I sent her,

00:25:30.410 --> 00:25:33.210
but this one contains her new status which is accepted.

00:25:33.210 --> 00:25:37.500
So that message is winding its way back through
the cloud, back to our server over here.

00:25:37.500 --> 00:25:47.670
So hopefully, we should actually see that pop up
in iCal depending on how fast email is going today.

00:25:47.670 --> 00:25:49.620
We'll wait for that to come through.

00:25:49.619 --> 00:25:53.839
In the meantime, we're going to
talk about another feature of iCal.

00:25:53.839 --> 00:26:01.189
One of the additional features that we added is the
ability for attendees to provide private comments back

00:26:01.190 --> 00:26:03.970
to the organizer when they're replying to events.

00:26:03.970 --> 00:26:10.079
So for example, let's see, I put an
event here that I had created and Morgan

00:26:10.079 --> 00:26:12.559
and Wilfredo were both invited to this event.

00:26:12.559 --> 00:26:17.599
Now, Morgan actually declined this event and he actually
sent me a comment to explain why he was declining the event.

00:26:17.599 --> 00:26:20.069
He has to go pick up his kids.

00:26:20.069 --> 00:26:25.539
Wilfredo accepted the event and-- but he also sent me back
a comment saying that he was going to have to leave halfway

00:26:25.539 --> 00:26:29.809
through the event 'cause he has to go fly to Vegas
for a business meeting or a poker game or something.

00:26:29.809 --> 00:26:34.240
So you know, these are comments that
attendees are sending to the organizer.

00:26:34.240 --> 00:26:36.900
Now, other attendees don't get to see these comments.

00:26:36.900 --> 00:26:43.160
It's only the attendee and organizer pair, those two
people that actually get to see this particular comment.

00:26:43.160 --> 00:26:47.300
The actual process of sending a
comment to an organizer is very simple.

00:26:47.299 --> 00:26:52.779
So here I have a meeting that was proposed by
the CEO Chris, and he invited me to this meeting.

00:26:52.779 --> 00:26:57.869
I haven't replied to it yet but I'd
like to just send a comment back to him,

00:26:57.869 --> 00:27:00.659
so what are we going to say, "Good idea."

00:27:00.660 --> 00:27:07.860
OK, so I can just type my comment in and I can click Accept,
and that comment and that reply is now going back to Chris

00:27:07.859 --> 00:27:12.339
and in just the same way that we saw
Wilfredo's and Morgan's comments in this event,

00:27:12.339 --> 00:27:16.069
Chris will see my comment coming back in his event.

00:27:17.690 --> 00:27:18.480
So let's see.

00:27:18.480 --> 00:27:21.430
Oh, well, Elisa's reply has just come back in.

00:27:21.430 --> 00:27:22.980
We see a green check mark next to Elisa.

00:27:22.980 --> 00:27:27.099
And so that email message we sent out to Gmail
with the iCalendar attachment, she replied to,

00:27:27.099 --> 00:27:32.869
has made its way back to our server and iCal
Server with its new feature took that email in,

00:27:32.869 --> 00:27:36.869
passed out the iCalendar information, figured
out that Elisa said she was accepting the meeting

00:27:36.869 --> 00:27:39.149
and it updated my calendar automatically for me.

00:27:39.150 --> 00:27:41.580
So her participation status is automatically covered.

00:27:41.579 --> 00:27:47.960
So we can schedule with people, not just on
our server, but on the other systems as well.

00:27:51.099 --> 00:27:52.939
[Background applause] And you know, this should work on--

00:27:52.940 --> 00:27:57.019
with pretty much any system that knows how to handle
the iMIP protocol, and that's pretty much you know,

00:27:57.019 --> 00:27:59.660
most email calendar systems that are integrated together.

00:27:59.660 --> 00:28:05.540
So Google, Yahoo, Outlook and Exchange
can also do iMIP scheduling if needed.

00:28:05.539 --> 00:28:10.049
So let's look at a couple of other
features that have been added to iCal.

00:28:10.049 --> 00:28:15.139
One thing we can do in iCal, we have this
Inspector Window, we can drag these windows off

00:28:15.140 --> 00:28:18.780
and we can actually have multiple
Inspector Windows open at the same time

00:28:18.779 --> 00:28:21.899
so that we can see [background applause] multiple events.

00:28:23.420 --> 00:28:28.240
And another option that we have is if we go
to the Edit menu, we have this Show Inspector

00:28:28.240 --> 00:28:32.269
which gives us a Floating Inspector Window,
so that now, as you select different events

00:28:32.269 --> 00:28:36.839
that stays updated [background applause] and
synchronized with the event you're looking at.

00:28:39.009 --> 00:28:46.670
And one more feature that we have in iCal, let me--
let's take a look at this event here that I proposed.

00:28:46.670 --> 00:28:50.269
I'm going to look at the free/busy information for Friday.

00:28:50.269 --> 00:28:56.009
Now, if you look at the top row here, this is my free/busy
information, and you can see it shows me as free all day.

00:28:56.009 --> 00:28:58.950
But let's say I needed to go on vacation that day.

00:28:58.950 --> 00:29:02.150
I'd like to actually block that time out for everyone.

00:29:02.150 --> 00:29:08.340
A simple option to do that might be to go in
here and create an All Day Event, vacation.

00:29:08.339 --> 00:29:12.819
So if I go and do that, and I go back here and
look at my free/busy information, what do I see?

00:29:12.819 --> 00:29:14.980
Well, it's still showing me as free.

00:29:14.980 --> 00:29:16.910
So something didn't work quite right there.

00:29:16.910 --> 00:29:24.440
So what's actually happening here is that by default,
iCal actually creates All Day Events as being free.

00:29:24.440 --> 00:29:28.130
That's the behavior in Leopard and
that's the behavior in Snow Leopard.

00:29:28.130 --> 00:29:33.890
What's new in Snow Leopard is that you now have
the option to actually mark events as free or busy.

00:29:33.890 --> 00:29:36.930
So they can be free or blocking-time busy.

00:29:36.930 --> 00:29:43.750
Again, by default, All Day Events are marked as
free, and by default, Timed Events come up as busy.

00:29:46.670 --> 00:29:48.910
[Background applause] So it's a very simple
process for me to block the whole day.

00:29:48.910 --> 00:29:55.230
I can just mark this event as busy, click
Done, and if I go and pull up the availability,

00:29:55.230 --> 00:29:58.130
you see that I'm now blocked out for this entire day.

00:29:58.130 --> 00:30:02.050
So a very simple process to manage
the free/busy information.

00:30:02.049 --> 00:30:08.470
So those are some of the key features that we have for
Snow Leopard, iCal Plan [phonetic], we have the integration

00:30:08.470 --> 00:30:12.789
with Exchange, we have the new
CalDAV-scheduling support that's built in.

00:30:12.789 --> 00:30:16.789
I mean a lot of the work that's involved there is kind
of under the hood, but we have some of these new--

00:30:16.789 --> 00:30:25.619
new UI features and new user interaction capabilities to
enhance the calendaring experience for iCal on the desktop.

00:30:25.619 --> 00:30:27.199
>> So where do you want to go next?

00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:33.519
Well, we've been to our Suits Office and we've been to our
Twunk Office you know, it's kind of the end of the day.

00:30:33.519 --> 00:30:37.440
I need to, you know, hop on the
commute bus back into the city,

00:30:37.440 --> 00:30:39.450
but I've got a few things I'd like to check on my calendar.

00:30:39.450 --> 00:30:41.069
So how am I going to do that?

00:30:41.069 --> 00:30:45.009
Well, let's go over to iPhone.

00:30:45.009 --> 00:30:50.539
[ Pause ]

00:30:50.539 --> 00:30:52.569
>> OK, so we have iPhone.

00:30:52.569 --> 00:30:54.789
This is running iPhone 3.0.

00:30:54.789 --> 00:31:02.319
Now in iPhone 1.0 and 2.0, you were able to
actually synchronize your CalDAV Calendars

00:31:02.319 --> 00:31:07.029
with the iPhone using iTunes and a cable to connect the two.

00:31:07.029 --> 00:31:09.039
You can see that little cable here.

00:31:09.039 --> 00:31:18.000
Well, good news, I can pull this cable out, I can, you
know, throw it away, and we can now do CalDAV on the iPhone,

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:20.630
over the air, talking directly to the server.

00:31:20.630 --> 00:31:22.860
We don't need that tethering when-- [applause].

00:31:25.900 --> 00:31:26.910
So we can change events.

00:31:26.910 --> 00:31:27.800
We can modify events.

00:31:27.799 --> 00:31:31.930
We can see events, changes, get propagated to the phone.

00:31:31.930 --> 00:31:35.840
We can see all that over the air, no need for tethered sync.

00:31:35.839 --> 00:31:41.169
So let's actually pull up our calendar here,
and I'm going to go to our calendar view.

00:31:41.170 --> 00:31:45.590
So again, in iPhone 2.0, we had Exchange support.

00:31:45.589 --> 00:31:53.149
So here, we have an Exchange account that's set up and we
also have our new Twunk CalDAV accounts of that as well.

00:31:53.150 --> 00:31:59.970
And iPhone lets us aggregate the view of all these
calendars, so I can click the All Calendars option.

00:31:59.970 --> 00:32:09.660
And now I'm seeing the same events that we saw in iCal
where the Exchange is in red and Twunk iCal Server events

00:32:09.660 --> 00:32:14.230
in green, and these events showing up in
the same way that we get on the desktop.

00:32:14.230 --> 00:32:18.789
We get the same view on the phone, again, the
seamless integration, ubiquitous calendaring approach.

00:32:18.789 --> 00:32:21.710
So let's actually take a look at one of these events.

00:32:21.710 --> 00:32:23.930
So this is an event on the Exchange Server.

00:32:23.930 --> 00:32:27.779
Again, it's-- that's the event that
was booked by the CEO for breakfast.

00:32:27.779 --> 00:32:32.000
We can see information about you
know, who is invited to this event.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:34.660
We've got information about availability.

00:32:34.660 --> 00:32:36.519
We can set our own alarms.

00:32:36.519 --> 00:32:43.420
And at the bottom here, we have the option of
responding to the event with a suitable response.

00:32:43.420 --> 00:32:49.140
So I'm just going to click Accept here, and the
phone again, is going out to the Exchange Server,

00:32:49.140 --> 00:32:54.590
sending that response back through Exchange, and we'll see
that information get updated on the Exchange site as well.

00:32:54.589 --> 00:32:59.740
So let's say I want to create a
simple event on my iCal Server now.

00:32:59.740 --> 00:33:05.890
So I'm going to go in here and just
click the plus-sign and I'm just going

00:33:05.890 --> 00:33:15.960
to create a very simple event I
need to-- OK, pick up dinner.

00:33:15.960 --> 00:33:18.549
OK, so I'm done.

00:33:18.549 --> 00:33:21.619
OK, let's see, what time-- well I need
to do that probably in the evening.

00:33:21.619 --> 00:33:24.619
So I'm going to make this not too late in the evening.

00:33:24.619 --> 00:33:27.199
OK, 6 p.m. when I'm going home,
I got to remember to do that.

00:33:27.200 --> 00:33:34.240
Click down, yeah, I probably need to set myself
on the left, OK, 15 minutes, click down on there.

00:33:34.240 --> 00:33:35.359
OK, everything else looks OK.

00:33:35.359 --> 00:33:37.919
Yeah, that's in the right calendar, I can click Done.

00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:45.950
So that event 6 p.m. on Thursday, we just created
that on the phone to upload it to iCal server.

00:33:45.950 --> 00:33:48.940
So let's see, did we actually get that over here?

00:33:50.210 --> 00:33:55.140
Let's go back to our iCal and yes, here we
go, we've got that Pick Up Dinner Event.

00:33:55.140 --> 00:34:00.290
We created it on the iPhone, went out to the
iCal Server, any CalDAV client has connected

00:34:00.289 --> 00:34:05.099
that iCal Server will be able to see that event
update, and it will come back down to those clients.

