00:39:12.949 --> 00:39:20.099
So let me give you some updates on what's new
since the last time we talked about this stuff.

00:39:20.099 --> 00:39:22.940
So in iCal Server 2, we have a few things.

00:39:22.940 --> 00:39:27.200
One is we've got attendee lookup support, made
have we [phonetic] over HTTP Protocol now.

00:39:27.199 --> 00:39:32.449
What this means is that clients no longer
have to buy into Open Directory and do lookups

00:39:32.449 --> 00:39:37.250
through the directory services
API in order to look up attendees.

00:39:37.250 --> 00:39:42.639
That's much easier for setting up your clients and it's
way easier for your mobile clients that need to setup

00:39:42.639 --> 00:39:50.319
out on the open network because setting OD when you're
outside the firewall isn't the easiest thing in the world.

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:55.660
Also very cool is we got rid of Services Locators and those
weird schema extensions that we had in the directory systems

00:39:55.659 --> 00:39:58.579
that made it harder for you to
set up your directory especially

00:39:58.579 --> 00:40:05.989
if you are coming in from an OD Environment [applause].

00:40:05.989 --> 00:40:08.609
We worked really hard on performance in Snow Leopard.

00:40:08.610 --> 00:40:10.590
It's kind of the feel on the client's side.

00:40:10.590 --> 00:40:14.460
We took that to heart and the server side as well.

00:40:14.460 --> 00:40:20.789
>> And, you know, in Leopard, we could deploy those small
businesses and was a decent solution there, but frankly,

00:40:20.789 --> 00:40:24.469
like when you try to scale it a very
large business, it didn't work out.

00:40:24.469 --> 00:40:31.859
So we decided to suck it up and we were going to make
this work until we could deploy all of Apple worldwide.

00:40:31.860 --> 00:40:34.710
All of our employees are now using
iCal Server as of 2 weeks ago.

00:40:34.710 --> 00:40:39.949
We shut down Meeting Maker which we've been using for like
15-plus years and are now living on iCal Server [applause].

00:40:39.949 --> 00:40:51.549
Now if you want more of the scoop on that, you can head us
up at the lab, which is going to be downstairs after this.

00:40:51.550 --> 00:40:56.220
But short answer, running on one server
because we don't have clustering yet,

00:40:56.219 --> 00:41:01.449
so one server supports the entire company.

00:41:01.449 --> 00:41:06.269
Now, also on this server, we've got improved
client data validation, which you know,

00:41:06.269 --> 00:41:10.199
is important from the standards point of view because
you don't want a client putting data onto the server

00:41:10.199 --> 00:41:12.449
that another client is going to get confused by.

00:41:12.449 --> 00:41:16.559
So iCal Server is being a little more careful
about checking the data that's coming in.

00:41:16.559 --> 00:41:22.000
We've added support for-- we call them Implicit
Scheduling which is a very fundamental change

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:28.159
in the CalDAV Scheduling Protocol that
happened since we shipped Leopard until now.

00:41:28.159 --> 00:41:32.779
And that was actually a change that we drove
pretty hard, and basically moved a lot of the logic

00:41:32.780 --> 00:41:35.830
for scheduling from the client down to the server.

00:41:35.829 --> 00:41:37.679
And that means a few things.

00:41:37.679 --> 00:41:42.879
One is that the implementation for the scheduling
logic is in one place, so that if there are bugs,

00:41:42.880 --> 00:41:46.460
we can kind of rule that out as a server
update, and you can update your server rather

00:41:46.460 --> 00:41:50.150
than updating having many thousand
clients you've got out in your network.

00:41:50.150 --> 00:41:54.730
It also means that there's only one implementation,
therefore, it agrees with itself as supposed

00:41:54.730 --> 00:41:56.869
to different clients implementing the same logic

00:41:56.869 --> 00:42:04.539
and having slightly different interpretations,
possibly correct ones of the standard.

00:42:04.539 --> 00:42:08.090
We've also added Server-to-Client push notifications.

00:42:08.090 --> 00:42:13.620
This is based on the XMPP Protocol, and we've
added email invitations and use the Web Calendar.

00:42:13.619 --> 00:42:15.900
I'll get into these little more detail.

00:42:15.900 --> 00:42:19.150
Again, in implicit scheduling,
there's a big change in CalDAV.

00:42:19.150 --> 00:42:23.099
One of the other effects of doing this is
that it makes it easier to write a client,

00:42:23.099 --> 00:42:27.099
because you don't have to do the scheduling
work in the client, it's all on the server.

00:42:27.099 --> 00:42:32.630
The web client which is all done in JavaScript, now
we don't have to load up all of the scheduling logic

00:42:32.630 --> 00:42:39.869
into your browser, it just edits the event and
the server magically takes care of the rest.

00:42:39.869 --> 00:42:46.190
This also means that consistency on the server is
improved because if a client does some of the operations

00:42:46.190 --> 00:42:48.539
but not others, you can kind of
get into an inconsistent state.

00:42:48.539 --> 00:42:51.179
Now, because the server is doing it,
we can kind of have a better guarantee

00:42:51.179 --> 00:42:54.799
that all of access is going to be consistent.

00:42:54.800 --> 00:43:01.480
And again, with Leopard, if I invited a hundred people
to a meeting, the attendees aren't going to know

00:43:01.480 --> 00:43:05.610
about each other's participation status
until iCal sends updates to everybody.

00:43:05.610 --> 00:43:09.620
And in order to avoid doing a lot of
messaging, it doesn't do that very often.

00:43:09.619 --> 00:43:13.519
Now that the server is managing that,
everybody gets an update right away.

00:43:13.519 --> 00:43:16.820
And this actually helped a lot with the email invitations.

00:43:16.820 --> 00:43:20.400
The Server-to-Client Notifications
eliminate the need for iCal

00:43:20.400 --> 00:43:23.309
to repeatedly pull the server,
"Hey, do I have any new meetings?

00:43:23.309 --> 00:43:24.380
How about now?

00:43:24.380 --> 00:43:25.840
How about now?

00:43:25.840 --> 00:43:27.480
No? OK, how about now?"

00:43:27.480 --> 00:43:32.769
And so, now the server says, "Hey, iCal, now is
a good time for you to check up for new meetings

00:43:32.769 --> 00:43:38.259
because we have new data for you," and that helps with
server load, and it also helps with the user experience,

00:43:38.260 --> 00:43:42.690
because it feels a lot more real-time for the user
when they get notifications right away as supposed

00:43:42.690 --> 00:43:45.300
to next time iCal gets around to checking.

00:43:45.300 --> 00:43:51.720
But a user Web Calendar-- now we had a Web Calendar
in Leopard but it was kind of limited to groups.

00:43:51.719 --> 00:43:56.899
Now every user can log in and they can edit meetings and
schedule, and as you saw that was a very rich experience,

00:43:56.900 --> 00:44:00.490
you can do free/busy lookups, you can
actually do all of the things you can do

00:44:00.489 --> 00:44:05.169
in iCal, but now you can do them all on the web.

00:44:05.170 --> 00:44:11.010
Email invitations allow you to invite people who
are not on your server to a meeting, and as you saw,

00:44:11.010 --> 00:44:15.570
Cyrus invited somebody who had a Google account, but
similarly, you can do the same thing with a Yahoo account

00:44:15.570 --> 00:44:22.240
or somebody who's using Outlook at whatever email system
they're using because most calendar agents out there

00:44:22.239 --> 00:44:29.089
in the world already understand iMIP and almost all of them
understand iTIP so that they can get these attachments,

00:44:29.090 --> 00:44:34.630
open them up and then in that calendar agent, you
can reply "Yes" or "No" or "Maybe" to the meeting.

00:44:34.630 --> 00:44:37.970
Now, we went through some effort
to make those emails look pretty.

00:44:37.969 --> 00:44:40.629
So as you saw, there's an HTML formatted message in there.

00:44:40.630 --> 00:44:46.349
There is also a plain text alternative,
and then you've got the attachment.

00:44:46.349 --> 00:44:53.110
Most mail agents will process that for you and the
replies that come back actually don't go back to iCal

00:44:53.110 --> 00:44:54.780
or to your email client and then to iCal.

00:44:54.780 --> 00:44:59.769
They go back straight to the server which because of
implicit scheduling needs that the server can then process

00:44:59.769 --> 00:45:02.590
that and then update everybody's status immediately.

00:45:02.590 --> 00:45:04.539
So everybody knows what's going on.

00:45:04.539 --> 00:45:13.110
So this is what that looks like in Apple's Mail
Client, rendered in WebKit, so embedded you there.

00:45:13.110 --> 00:45:15.289
This is what it looks like in Gmail.

00:45:15.289 --> 00:45:16.309
Again, it's pretty similar.

00:45:16.309 --> 00:45:19.980
Gmail gives you a little effort
to accept that right in there.

00:45:19.980 --> 00:45:26.260
And in Apple's Mail, you can actually have them
automatically forward, straight into iCal for you.

00:45:26.260 --> 00:45:30.600
Now, there are some other features in Snow Leopard
Server that are relevant to the calendaring space.

