00:46:08.670 --> 00:46:12.000
to certain users, and other certain conditions.

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:14.349
And we've integrated entirely with the mail servers.

00:46:14.349 --> 00:46:18.989
So that when you configure iCal
Server, it just sets up iCal within a--

00:46:18.989 --> 00:46:22.969
sets up mail with an account that we can
do this email delivery stuff-- stuff was.

00:46:22.969 --> 00:46:30.589
If you're not using our built-in Mail Server, you can set
up, you know, configure IMAP and SMTP for iCal Servers

00:46:30.590 --> 00:46:33.010
to use in order to facilitate all of that as well.

00:46:33.010 --> 00:46:35.650
So again, it's all standard based.

00:46:35.650 --> 00:46:40.650
iCal has got a whole bunch of new stuff for you as well.

00:46:40.650 --> 00:46:45.570
We've-- they've done a lot of work to support this
implicit scheduling work that we've been doing to make

00:46:45.570 --> 00:46:50.690
that flow better in the-- in the
user experience on the client's side.

00:46:50.690 --> 00:46:53.809
They of course, have to have support for
these push notifications and subscribe

00:46:53.809 --> 00:46:55.989
to them in order to take advantage of that.

00:46:55.989 --> 00:47:00.819
And again, they are now doing these attendee
lookups via CalDAV and not through Open Directory

00:47:00.820 --> 00:47:04.170
which allows you not to have to bind to-- to an OD Server.

00:47:04.170 --> 00:47:08.200
They've added support for this
attendee comments and Cyrus demoed that.

00:47:08.199 --> 00:47:11.859
So now you can reply to a meeting that
